  "original_title": "Sri Lanka\u2019 CPC may need Treasury\u2019s help to repay India\u2019s $700 mln \u2013 minister",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka\u2019 CPC may need Treasury\u2019s help to repay India\u2019s $700 mln \u2013 minister",
      "author": "",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT \u2013 Sri Lanka\u2019s state-run fuel retailer Ceylon Petroleum Corporation will need the help of the island nation\u2019s Treasury when the repayment of $700 million Indian credit line starts, Power and Energy Minister Kanchan Wijesekera said.",
        "Sri Lanka has already borrowed $700 million from India to finance its fuel requirement from March and the last shipment arrived in on June 16 under the two credit line \u2013 $500 million fuel credit time and $200 million essential commodity credit line.",
        "The credit lines for one year and Minister Wijesekera said the CPC has already started collecting rupees for the repayment, which starts in March 2023.",
        "\u201cOur responsibility is to collect the rupee value pay the $700 million. The payment starts in March next year,\u201d Wijesekera told reporters at a media briefing in Colombo on Sunday (26) at the Ministry of Power and Energy.",
        "\u201cOf course we will have to get some sort of support from treasury as well because, even though during the $700 million credit line the prices were adjusted, initially in March and April, the CPC and IOC were selling fuel at a much lower price than what we had import at. So there will be a bridging gap. That gap will be bridged by treasury.\u201d",
        "Wijesekera last month said a fresh $500 million fuel credit which is under discussion will have a grace period of more than one year.",
        "Sri Lanka has been looking for the fresh credit line as the CPC has failed to ensure any shipment since the last fuel cargo came from the Indian credit line on June 16. (Colombo/June 27/2022)"
      ],
